<h2>How to use the live sampler</h2>

<p>
First of all you need to add at least one <strong>sample channel</strong>, then arm it with the channel's <strong>arm button</strong> <img src="{{ url('img/docs/arm-button.png') }}" alt="Arm button" title="Arm button" class="inline" />. You can of course arm multiple channels. When you are ready, click on the <strong>input rec</strong> button <img src="{{ url('img/docs/input-recording-button.png') }}" alt="Input rec button" title="Input rec button" class="inline" /> on the main transport or press <span class="code">end</span> to enable the sampler: channels with active input will turn blue.</p>

<p>The master play will start automatically, since recording a sound doesn't make sense with the master play turned off. The sampler works in <em>overdub mode</em> by default: the messages coming from the soundcard are being	continuously summed to the existing data until the sampler is halted.</p>

<h2>Live FX processor</h2>

<p>
The arm button on each sample channel enables the <strong>input monitor</strong>. This way you hear what you're actually playing, previously processed by the plugins stack (if any). If you don't enable the sampler (<strong>input rec</strong> button <img src="{{ url('img/docs/input-recording-button.png') }}" alt="Input rec button" title="Input rec button" class="inline" /> or <span class="code">end</span>), Giada won't record anything and turns into a live FX processor instead.</p>

<p>You can accomplish the same result by using the <strong>stream linker</strong>, the button between the input and the output meter <img src="{{ url('img/docs/input-output-linker.png') }}" alt="Input to output linker" title="Input to output linker" class="inline" />. Enable it and you will be able to hear what you're playing.</p>
